{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473616","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473616"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:11:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:11:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2576"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2576","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2576"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.11,0.01,0.74,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2576"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48909"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2576","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2576"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2576"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33909"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1077"},{"type":"tags","id":"1131"},{"type":"tags","id":"1259"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2703"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2717"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8421"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8555"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13362"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28600"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48909","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48909"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 12-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent due to pain in his right knee for the past five weeks. One week before the onset of his knee pain, the patient had a fall on the grass while playing soccer but was able to continue playing. Initially, his right knee pain worsened with activity, such as jogging. For the past week, he has complained of constant dull pain. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His height is at the 50th percentile and weight is at the 97th percentile. He is able to bear weight but walks with a noticeable limp. There is no knee joint warmth, swelling, or erythema, and movements of the knee are normal. There is limited internal rotation and abduction of the hip on the right side.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Legg-Calv\u00e9-Perthes disease","Osgood-Schlatter disease","Septic arthritis","Slipped capital femoral epiphysis","Transient synovitis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient most likely has a \u003Cstrong\u003Eslipped capital femoral epiphysis\u003C/strong\u003E (SCFE). SCFE typically affects children aged 10-16 years, with obesity being a common risk factor. It is caused by shearing force at the proximal femoral physis, leading to posteroinferior displacement of the proximal femoral epiphysis. Patients usually present with acute, chronic, or acute-on-chronic dull pain in the thigh, knee, groin, or hip, often accompanied by a limp. Physical examination characteristically reveals limited internal rotation and abduction of the hip, which is consistent with this patient\u0027s presentation. X-ray is usually diagnostic, showing posterior and inferior displacement of the femoral head in relation to the femoral neck. Treatment typically involves surgical fixation with pinning of the femoral head.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELegg-Calv\u00e9-Perthes disease\u003C/strong\u003E is avascular necrosis of the femoral head, usually affecting children aged 4-10 years. While it can present with an antalgic gait and hip or knee pain, it typically occurs in a younger age group than this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsgood-Schlatter disease\u003C/strong\u003E is an overuse injury characterised by traction apophysitis at the insertion of the quadriceps tendon on the tibial tubercle. It typically presents with knee pain and proximal tibial swelling, which are not described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeptic arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E is a joint infection that usually presents with fever, joint pain, and restricted range of motion. The patient\u0027s normal vital signs, ability to bear weight, and absence of joint swelling or erythema make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransient synovitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically affects children aged 4-10 years and presents with hip pain and decreased range of motion. However, symptoms usually resolve within one to four weeks, unlike this patient\u0027s persistent pain for five weeks.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A limp in adolescents should always raise the possibility of a slipped capital femoral epiphysis.","Slipped capital femoral epiphysis typically presents with hip, groin, thigh, or knee pain in obese adolescents aged 10-16 years.","Limited internal rotation and abduction of the hip are characteristic physical examination findings in slipped capital femoral epiphysis."],"references":["Millis MB. SCFE: clinical aspects, diagnosis, and classification. J Child Orthop. 2017 Apr;11(2):93-98. doi: 10.1302/1863-2548-11-170025."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33909"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2576"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33909","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33909"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-19T14:13:46+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-08T16:29:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2576"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48909"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group"